Subject:    Can nameservers give different answers to different requestors?
From:       <a href="?a=95837784000008&r=1&w=2">Ben Cranston &lt;ZBEN () UMD2 ! UMD ! EDU&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198607">1986-07-18 19:39:06</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026739&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026739&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

&gt; Date:     Fri, 18 Jul 1986 14:48:14 EDT
&gt; From:     John Wagner &lt;MAINTCMS@PUCC&gt;

&gt;&gt; I am not sure from the standard if the nameserver is allowed to look at
&gt;&gt; *my* Internet address and maybe tell me something different than it would
&gt;&gt; tell *you*...  Anybody feel confident enough to comment on this?

&gt; As I understood it, the requirement is that you must have a minimum
&gt; of 2 nameservers supporting the node (spaced across the country I
&gt; assume). I don't think a maximum is specified.  Why couldn't
&gt; different name servers return different responses?

This is an independant question, though I don't think in the general case
you want the two redundant nameservers disagreeing.  What I meant to ask is
if a nameserver, when asked about an RSCS-only node, is allowed to return
umd2 for east coast requesters, wiscvm for midwest requesters, and ucbjade
for west coast requesters.

We're not addressing doability (like how to map network addresses to region),
just the legality of returning different answers to different people.

